{"title_page": "Arab states of the Persian Gulf", "text_new": "{{rewrite|date=June 2018}}<!---------\n  Note: Please see the talk page before changing \"Persian Gulf\" to \"Arab\" or \"Arabian Gulf\".\n ---------->\n[[File:Arab_Gulf_States_english.png|thumbnail|260px|The [[Persian Gulf]]'s coastline skirts seven Arab countries on its western shores and [[Iran]] to the east. ([[Oman]]'s [[Musandam peninsula]] meets the Persian gulf at the [[Strait of Hormuz]])]]\n\nThe '''Arab states of the Persian Gulf''' are the seven [[Arab world|Arab states]] which border the [[Arabian Gulf]], namely [[Bahrain]], [[Kuwait]], [[Iraq]], [[Oman]], [[Qatar]], [[Saudi Arabia]] and the [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE).<ref>{{cite book |author1=Mary Ann T\u00e9treault |author2=Gwenn Okruhlik |author3=Andrzej Kapiszewski |title=Political Change in the Arab Gulf States: Stuck in Transition |url=https://www.rienner.com/title/Political_Change_in_the_Arab_Gulf_States_Stuck_in_Transition |quote=The authors first focus on the politics of seven Gulf states: Bahrain, Iraq, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and the UAE. |year=2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xIJBiLdNJm4C&pg=PP55&dq |title=World Migration 2005 Costs and Benefits of International Migration |publisher=International Organization for Migration |page=53 |year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Official to Tour Arabian Gulf Arab Lands |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/05/05/world/us-official-to-tour-persian-gulf-arab-lands.html |quote=A leading American diplomat will start a trip to Iraq and six other Arab countries of the Persian Gulf region this week to discuss the Iran-Iraq war, Administration officials said today. |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |year=1987}}</ref> All of these nations except Iraq are part of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gcc-sg.org/en-us/Pages/default.aspx|title=\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0648\u0646 \u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|website=www.gcc-sg.org}}</ref> and prefer to use the term \"[[Persian Gulf naming dispute|Arabian Gulf]]\" rather than the historical name of the [[Persian Gulf]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Henderson|first1=Simon|title=Understanding the Gulf States|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/understanding-the-gulf-states|website=The Washington Institute|accessdate=1 June 2016|date=Spring 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nSome states are [[constitutional monarchies]] with elected parliaments. [[Bahrain]] (''[[National Assembly (Bahrain)|Majlis al Watani]]'') and [[Kuwait]] (''[[National Assembly (Kuwait)|Majlis al Ummah]]'') have legislatures with members elected by the population.\n\nThe Sultanate of Oman also has an advisory council (''Majlis ash-Shura'') that is popularly elected. In the UAE, a federation of seven monarchical emirates, the [[Federal National Council (United Arab Emirates)]] functions only as an advisory body, but some of its members are now chosen via a limited [[electoral college]] nominated by the seven rulers. Saudi Arabia remains a [[hereditary monarchy]] with limited political representation. In Qatar, an elected national parliament has been mooted and is written into the new constitution, but elections are yet to be held.<ref>Gerd Nonneman, \"Political Reform in the Gulf Monarchies: From Liberalisation to Democratisation? A Comparative Perspective\", in Anoushiravan Ehteshami and Steven Wright (eds.)(2007), ''Reform in the Middle East Oil Monarchies'', {{ISBN|978-0-86372-323-0}}, pp. 3-45.</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n{{Main article|Culture of Eastern Arabia|Arab cuisine of the Persian Gulf}}\n\nSoap operas are important national pastimes in the Gulf Arab region. They are most popular during the time of [[Ramadan]], when families gather to break their fast. Most of these soap operas are based in [[Kuwait]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.broadcastprome.com/content-creation/big-plans-for-small-screens/#.VwhXXvl97IV|title=Big plans for small screens|work=BroadcastPro Me|quote=Around 90% of Khaleeji productions take place in Kuwait.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Constantinos |last= Papavassilopoulos|url=https://technology.ihs.com/496709/osn-targets-new-markets-by-enriching-its-arabic-content-offering|title=OSN targets new markets by enriching its Arabic content offering|work=[[IHS Inc.]]|date=10 April 2014}}</ref> Kuwaiti soap operas are the most-watched soap operas in the Persian Gulf region.<ref name=\"fattah\">{{cite news |first=Nawara |last=Fattahova |url=http://news.kuwaittimes.net/first-kuwaiti-horror-movie-to-be-set-in-haunted-palace-chilling-news-for-film-buffs/|title=First Kuwaiti horror movie to be set in \u2018haunted\u2019 palace|newspaper=Kuwait Times|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Fahad|last=Al Mukrashi|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/oman/omanis-turn-their-backs-on-local-dramas-1.1568086|title=Omanis turn their backs on local dramas|newspaper=Gulf News|date=22 August 2015|quote=Kuwait\u2019s drama industry tops other Gulf drama as it has very prominent actors and actresses, enough scripts and budgets, produces fifteen serials annually at least.}}</ref> Although usually performed in the Kuwaiti dialect, they have been shown with success as far away as [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Peter |last=Mansfield |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uzy_AAAAIAAJ&q|title=Kuwait: vanguard of the Gulf |publisher=Hutchinson |date=1990 |page=113 |quote=Some Kuwaiti soap operas have become extremely popular and, although they are usually performed in the Kuwaiti dialect, they have been shown with success as far away as Tunisia.}}</ref> Kuwaiti [[popular culture]], in the form of theatre, radio and television soap opera, flourishes and is exported to neighbouring Arab states of the Persian Gulf.<ref name=\"cliv\">{{cite book|author=Clive Holes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8E0Rr1xY4TQC&pg=PA75|title=Modern Arabic: Structures, Functions, and Varieties|date=2004|page=75|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=978-1-58901-022-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ali Alawi|url=http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/features/alis-roadtrip-from-bahrain-to-kuwait-photos_13423|title=Ali's roadtrip from Bahrain to Kuwait (PHOTOS)|quote=The trip to Kuwait \u2013 a country that has built a deep connection with people in the Persian Gulf thanks to its significant drama productions in theater, television, and even music \u2013 started with 25 kilometers of spectacular sea view}}</ref> Darb El Zalag, Khalti Gmasha, and Ruqayya wa Sabika are among the most important television productions in the Persian Gulf region.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theasian.asia/archives/87665|title=Kuwaiti Drama Museum: formulating thoughts of the Gulf|date=23 May 2014}}</ref> Kuwait is widely considered the cultural capital of the Arab states of the Persian Gulf region,<ref name=\"mdt\">{{cite news|url=http://www.muscatdaily.com/Archive/Features/Kuwait-an-urban-spectacle-3xlc|title=Kuwait an urban spectacle|work=[[Muscat Daily]]|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljarida.com/articles/1461965247680716900/|title= \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647\u2026 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0643 \u064a\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a|work=[[Al-Jarida]]|language=Arabic|date=28 July 2011}}</ref> frequently dubbed the \"[[Hollywood]] of the Gulf\" due to the popularity of its Arabic television soap operas and theatre.{{refn|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mbc.net/ar/programs/banat-sokkar-nabat/articles/%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%85-%D8%AD%D8%B3%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%AD%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89--%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC----%D9%88%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%A3-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%82%D9%88%D9%82-%D9%81%D9%8A--%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%B1-%D9%86%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AA-.html|title=\u0645\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 \u062a\u0631\u062d\u0644 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \"\u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c\".. \u0648\u062a\u062a\u0628\u0631\u0623 \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0642\u0648\u0642 \u0641\u064a \"\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a \u0633\u0643\u0631 \u0646\u0628\u0627\u062a\"|work=[[Middle East Broadcasting Center|MBC]]|language=Arabic|date=29 August 2015|access-date=3 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011010019/http://www.mbc.net/ar/programs/banat-sokkar-nabat/articles/%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%85-%D8%AD%D8%B3%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%AD%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89--%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC----%D9%88%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%A3-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%82%D9%88%D9%82-%D9%81%D9%8A--%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%B1-%D9%86%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AA-.html|archive-date=11 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.alwatanvoice.com/arabic/news/2015/07/08/740666.html|title=\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 : \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u064a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c|language=Arabic|date=8 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elfann.com/news/show/1059017/%D9%85%D9%86%D9%89-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%84%D9%88%D8%B4%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AA-%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC-%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%82%D8%B5%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%B4%D9%87%D8%B1%D8%A9|title=\u0645\u0646\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u0648\u0634\u064a: \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u064a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c \u0648\u064a\u0642\u0635\u062f\u0648\u0646\u0647\u0627 \u0644\u0644\u0634\u0647\u0631\u0629 |l